com.avaya.csta.physical

Class ButtonIDConstants

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.avaya.csta.physical.ButtonIDConstants

  • public class ButtonIDConstants
extends java.lang.Object
    An enumeration for Button ID, also referred to as button address. A button ID reflects the location of a button on a device and is used to uniquely identify any given button on the device. In contrast, the button function indicates what a button does. Multiple buttons on a phone may have the same function, such as call appearances, but no two buttons on a phone have the same ID.

    This class lists the basic Button IDs for the 4624 IP telephone set and the 6424, 8410D, and 8434D DCP telephone sets. These are generic references to the standard set of buttons found on these phone sets. There are many other phone sets containing additional button IDs not found in this class.

    The function performed by a given button ID can be administered differently for each extension. For details on determining the button ID for a specific button function, see the ButtonFunctionConstants class.

    Button IDs are used in service requests, responses, and events. In particular, they are used in these methods:

    • PhysicalDeviceServices.getButtonInformation() returns the list of button IDs on the specified device. Use ButtonItem.getButton() to obtain a given button's ID.
    • PhysicalDeviceServices.pressButton() requires the button ID to be specified. Use PressButton.setButton() to specify which button to press.
    • PhysicalDeviceListener.buttonInformationChanged() returns the button ID of a button that changed. Use ButtonInformationEvent.getButton() to obtain the changed button's ID.

    Here is an example of how you would use ButtonIDConstants in specifying which button to press: 

     ButtonPress request = new ButtonPress();
 request.setDevice(device);
 request.setButton(ButtonIDConstants.CONFERENCE);
